The project designed a unique infrastructure that supports computing functions to be implemented at the extreme edge of today’s networks, i.e., in edge gateways that are proliferating in various home and mobile settings. In particular, the core objective of the project is to make the common WiFi Access Point or AP (usually found in a regular home gateway) as a true computing platform and use it to support an effective edge computing abstraction.
For this, the project proposed a framework called ParaDrop which needs to design and implement multiple complementary components:
(i)     a lightweight virtualization framework on the WiFi AP that allows independent third-party services to be deployed on-demand implemented with container technologies;
(ii)    a cloud-based network scaffolding framework to manage deployment of these container instances (being called chutes);
(iii)    a "Chute Store" that allows third-party developers to deploy and manage such chutes in a dynamic and flexible manner and utilizes a software defined networking framework for such management;
(iv)    an enhanced API for such chutes that leverages unique knowledge of the wireless context of mobile devices in the vicinity of the APs.
Many applications have been developed that showcases the benefits of this overall framework, ranging from smart transportation, smart buildings, and smart environments. Examples included improved transit and driving analytics, and more sustainable buildings. The project has been released through the open-source
 pathway, and the findings have been incorporated into the classroom materials at UW-Madison. In addition, the project team has conducted multiple tutorials that allow a broader computing audience is able to learn how to deploy use such infrastructure.



